akes an original, intersectional approach to these issues by building upon the gendered mediation thesis to argue that political communication and reporting reinforces impressions of politics as a masculine domain that privileges men and treats women as outsiders. Organized into three sections, the book investigates politicians’ gendered strategies for shaping their own and others’ public images, the gendered characteristics of media coverage of politicians, and voter reactions to these self-presentations and media depictions. By examining how sexuality, race, age, and class intersect with gender to produce differing political identities and responses, the contributors make new theoretical and empirical interventions into research on gender and political communication. Their findings have profound implications for democracy not only in Canada but for democratic political systems elsewhere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aSex discrimination in political culturezCanada. 0aSex discriminationzCanada. 0aWomen legislatorszCanadaxPublic opinion. 0aWomen legislatorszCanada. 0aWomen politicianszCanadaxPublic opinion. 0aWomen politicianszCanada. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzCanadaxPublic opinion. 0aWomenxPolitical activityzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Women in Politics.2bisacsh1 aBesco, Randy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBest, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDumitrescu, Delia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEveritt, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEveritt, Joanna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGaudet, Derek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGerrits, Bailey, econtributor.4